What is my innovation feature? 

Considering my background in marketing and communications,I have decided to add to the conference database the feature that supports
one of the main purposes of conferences: NETWORKING .

Professional relationships often grow through shared interests and mutual contacts, so I proposed a networking menu that recommends
connections through the friend-of-a-friend who are not directly connected, by up to 4 levels.

Using Neo4j graph relationships, this innovation acts as a simple recommendation engine, and it shows how the database can be used
to store connections, as well as generate meaningful networking opportunities for conference attendees.

How the Suggested Connections Feature Works

1. The user selects the Suggested Connections menu option and enters an attendee ID.
2. The system queries the Neo4j database to find the attendee’s direct connections.
3. It, then, searches for friends-of-friends (second-degree connections) linked through those direct connections.
4. Existing direct connections and the attendee themselves are excluded, so only new potential connections are suggested.
5. Suggested attendees are returned as networking recommendations, optionally ranked by number of mutual connections.
6. A Neo4j graph visualisation can also be used to display the attendee’s network and highlight suggested new connections.

This is implemented using Neo4j graph traversal, matching mutual connections and filtering out attendees already connected.


Source: https://neo4j.com/docs/java-reference/current/java-embedded/traversal/
